    "NY Session"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "New York Session is a high-volatility kill zone in EST, typically 08:30–11:00 for indices (07:00–10:00 for Forex), with an afternoon session (13:30–16:00) for indices. It delivers the distribution phase of AMD after Asia accumulation and London manipulation, offering entries catalyzed by 08:30 and 09:30 news. In Seek and Destroy conditions, New York consolidates back into range.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Set chart time zone to EST and identify the New York kill zone according to the instrument: Forex NY AM 07:00–10:00, Indices NY AM 08:30–11:00, Indices NY PM 13:30–16:00. Use a sessions indicator to automatically draw session boxes and record session highs/lows.",
    "Assess prior sessions: if London swept both sides of the Asia range without displacement, or if London already expanded to cover most of the daily range, expect New York to consolidate (Seek and Destroy conditions). High-impact news (CPI, FOMC, NFP) ahead also increases consolidation probability.",
    "In normal expansionary conditions, look for the 08:30 or 09:30 news driver to coincide with a liquidity sweep into a higher time frame point of interest. After a London reversal, expect New York to continue in the direction of the daily bias.",
    "If New York opens with aggressive expansion followed by a sweep of a session high/low, treat that sweep as the reversal point for the session before continuation.",
    "Within NY AM, the 10:00–11:00 Silver Bullet hour provides a refined window for entries targeting liquidity draws.",
    "Confirm entries on a lower time frame (3- or 5-minute) with a change in state of delivery, such as a close through opposing candles.",
    "If price exits the London range during New York but fails to displace and returns inside, treat it as a deviation and target rebalancing back toward range equilibrium (0.5 level).",
    "In the context of Next Day Model, after identifying key structures on the daily chart (e.g., Daily FVG, Order Block, liquidity levels), switch to a 15-minute chart during the New York Session to find precise entries.",
    "At the start of New York Session, observe price action from the Midnight Open to identify micro structures like 15-minute FVG or Order Block.",
    "During New York Session, price typically moves toward the higher timeframe targets identified from the previous day (e.g., Draw on Liquidity, Sell Side Liquidity).",
    "New York Session is the execution window after skipping Monday and waiting for price to reach higher timeframe levels on the following day."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "New York is the distribution session of AMD, the primary entry window. Align with daily bias, wait for 08:30/09:30 news to sweep liquidity into HTF POIs (order blocks, fair value gaps). Enter on lower timeframe change in state of delivery targeting standard-deviation projections of London manipulation or 2R. NY PM offers a second expansion; the 10:00–11:00 Silver Bullet hour is high-probability. In Seek and Destroy conditions, fade deviations outside London range back to equilibrium (0.5) and opposite range side; avoid breakouts. Asia/London ranges and daily open act as rebalancing magnets. In Next Day Model, execute trades only during New York Session using 15-minute chart for entry.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Trading New York as an expansion/breakout session when London swept both sides of Asia without displacement (Seek and Destroy conditions).",
    "Participating in New York when London has already expanded to cover most of the daily range, expecting another large directional move.",
    "Taking entries before the 08:30 or 09:30 news driver creates a liquidity sweep and forms the session low/high.",
    "Treating an aggressive expansion-out-expansion-back-in move as a retracement rather than a session reversal requiring a new sweep before continuation.",
    "Entering without aligning the daily, mid-term, and lower time frame structure into the New York window, or failing to check upcoming high-impact news that causes consolidation.",
    "Using the wrong time zone (not EST), causing kill zone misalignment especially around daylight savings.",
    "Applying the Forex NY AM window (07:00–10:00) to indices instead of the correct 08:30–11:00 window.",
    "Cluttering the chart with default session labels instead of configuring indicator settings (colors/times) for the traded instrument.",
    "Executing trades on Monday instead of skipping to Tuesday or later New York Session as per Next Day Model.",
    "Entering New York Session without a predefined higher timeframe target from the daily chart, leading to lack of a clear trading plan.",
    "Trading outside the New York Session window for Next Day Model setups, reducing probability."
  ],
